    <tr>
        <td style="background-color: #FFFFFF">
            <asp:HyperLink ID="HyperLink11" runat="server" Font-Size="X-Large">ETMs are designed for use in vehicles as fixed or mobile units, or in the form of electronic counter in locations other than train stations and buses.
Onboard Electronic Ticket Machines (ETMs) are most commonly used on bus services, but can also be used on other modes of transportation.
In a typical mode of operation, tariff commodities, tariff rules and prices (eg as tariff tables) are stored in his ETM memory.
The driver or conductor selects the function, ticket type and fare according to the customer`s request and the ticket is issued by ETM.
ETMs are often used as the central (or &quot;master&quot;) ITS device in a vehicle.
It can host configuration data for other devices and receive and store transaction data.</asp:HyperLink>
            <br />
            <br />
            <asp:HyperLink ID="HyperLink12" runat="server" Font-Size="X-Large">The electronic tag holds a record of driver-shift events, as supplied from the ETM, in addition to the unique fare-box ID.
When fare-boxes are emptied, a reader scans its electronic tag and knows which vehicle the unit belongs to and which drivers are accountable for which proportion of income.
In-vehicle ticket sales can also be undertaken by ticket vendors operating handheld electronic ticket issuing machines.
Data is recorded within these devices so that at the end of a shift the units can be connected to a computer system to download the information.
In addition, this type of system, like other in-vehicle methods of ticket issuing, is generally restricted to cash transactions, unable to accept credit/debit card payment due a lack of continuous wireless internet connection.
Electronic ticket issuing machines provided at stations, stops or terminals tend to be kiosk type systems using keypad or touch screen type user interfaces.
These units can be dedicated electronic ticket issuing machines or multifunctional systems offering additional passenger information or infotainment functions.</asp:HyperLink>
            <br />
            <br />
            <asp:HyperLink ID="HyperLink13" runat="server" Font-Size="X-Large">Off-vehicle systems are usually connected to an in-station computer system (wired or wireless connection) which is connected to central accounting and statistical management computer system at a control centre.</asp:HyperLink>
